I am looking for any and all medieval weapons, primarily I am looking for morning stars and axes, but as always, I will take a look at everything you have. Let me start with my standard boilerplate:


       I cannot accept any fake, 'faux' or 'display' weapons. These weapons will be disarmed(de-sharpened) and distributed to my SCA group for medieval re-enactments. The morning stars, in case you're curious, are for my personal collection, and will be kept sharp. There's no real way to de-sharpen a spiked ball anyways. So, any who offer up weapons will be required to prove that they are not display weapons(often giving me the company name is sufficient; I can find it from there and look at its specifications). Unless you are giving them away for free, I have no extra money for non-functioning weaponry(but I will take free ones off your hands!). These are not wall-hangers; they will spend their lives in the mud-and-blood of medieval combat, and as such must be built like real weapons.

    A word about material; I will not accept stainless steel. Anything over 12" and made from stainless is hilariously brittle and can't hold an edge, so I avoid it wherever I can. Carbon steel is the material they used to be made of, so that is my preferred choice. I will consider iron but I don't care for it's weight.


    Oh, and this ad includes armor! You have a suit of armor? Let me know! Even just helmets, greaves, chainmail, etc. All is fair game.

      I was going to include a paragraph describing what I'm looking for, but as there are literally thousands of medieval weapons and designs, it's impossible to name them all. So, let's keep it simple. I'm looking for any weapon styled pre-1650, and will consider weapons styled after. Let me be clear, I am not looking for actual medieval weapons. Reproductions or custom-made are the ones I'm after. European is my favored style, Germanic-Gothic if we're being specific, but I will, again, look at whatever you have.



Regards Armslist, let's see what you've got.



Thomas

title: Want To Buy:  What is a pre ban gun
postcontent:
Ok 1st off a preban gun. Most on here are not truthful about what they have they will post a yugo when it is clearly century arms gun not a true yugo ect. 2nd things to look at 1st a preban gun will have a bayo lug on most of them aks for example, on a fal as another example all preban guns will have a sear cut out and made on the same receiver that it was manufactured on not a imbel or ds receiver this is not a true preban gun nor is a ak with another name on the receiver unless it has both names which some importers do ....  im just sick of going after a specific gun only to find out not only is it not a preban but it is not at all what the wienie posted..... hope this helps you understand the diff between the 2 and pick wisely you may not get what your after if you rush and dont ask the proper questions....
another example is this

FS/FT: Romaniun AK47 with ammo and Mags
while the title says its romanian it clearly is not as at least this time the guy put century arms as the reciever so it is a century arms gun built with romanian parts so it should be listed as such not the falsehood it is listed as...... as a romanian gun would be a preban and have the proper markings on the receiver to say such 

another exapmle 
Preban M1A national match
this one was clearly a preban gun and properly listed as such has the bayo lug ect. ....

just want these fools to be more truthful about what they have and how it is listed to keep some of us for falling for false claims of glory if it is not properly listed don't even think about touching it you are not getting what your paying for not to mention if they lie about what it is there are probably more problems they are not going to mention either. ....

title: For Sale:  Garand M1D - Springfield Arms with scope and flash hider
postcontent:
I am selling my Springfield Arms Garand M1D rifle.  This sale is for the rifle, scope, scope mount, flash hider and cheek pad. A grease pot will also be included so you can properly lubricate the firearm.
The receiver is Springfield Arms in the 1.18m range which dates it to February 1943. The barrel is dated 10-52. The stock has an SA JLH cartouche which dates it to the barrel when this firearm was converted. The receiver is marked SA 65 on the leg indicating it went through the re-arsenal process at Springfield Arms in 1965.
The scope optics are clear and the cross hairs in excellent condition.
I was told the scope mount is aftermarket. I am not sure of the flash hider, it may also be aftermarket. The rest of the gun is believed to be original GI.
Another interesting fact is the heel of the receiver was lead annealed. This can be seen in the coloration of the parkerizing in this area.
I have run a limited number of rounds through the gun. It is accurate with both scope and iron sights, but not zeroed in. The only issue I found is the clip does not latch in place when the bolt is open. The bolt has to be pulled back slightly for the clip to latch. I do not know what is causing this issue. As always, I suggest a gunsmith inspect the gun before shooting.

FTF - respond only if legally able to own this firearm
No felons - WI resident - bill of sale - WI photo ID required.

Additional photos are available, however, I only respond to requests via phone - include your name and phone number please.
No phone number, no reply

title: For Sale/Trade:  Pennies!  Hey numismatists - here is the motherload!
postcontent:
My mother collected change her whole life.  Decades of coins dropped in jars.  These are the pennies.  We've done a quick visual sort to separate the wheats and the post 1982 ones (quick is relative, it took forever).  There is no doubt we missed some of both, but these are the remainder, 1959-1982.  If your hobby involves picking through coins to find that rare treasure, this bunch should keep you busy for a very, very, long time.  I haven't the patience for it. I guess some people also buy them as an investment due to copper content. I have a few ounces short of 140 pounds. Based on ebay prices and trying to stay a little low and get this done, I'll sell them for 1.5 cents per.  This is of course for the bunch, so that would be $304.  I understand that this is somewhere less than the melt value, so I will not drop the price. 

Sent a reply with your phone number, and I'll try to answer any questions.   

I would also be open to a trade for firearms, let me know what you have to trade, and I'll let you know if I'm interested.
